Interpreting Results¶

TODO: Pass alpha¶

If the p-value is small (< 0.05), it suggests that the variable is not independent of species, meaning it is significantly associated.¶

If the p-value is large (> 0.05), there is no evidence of dependence, meaning the variable does not vary significantly across species.¶

Interpretation¶

Higher MI scores indicate features that have a stronger dependency on species classification.¶

Lower MI scores suggest weaker relationships or redundant features.¶

Categorical variables (e.g., island, sex) may show high MI scores due to species-specific distributions.¶

This analysis helps in feature selection, dimensionality reduction, and understanding which variables are most influential in predicting¶

species.¶

Interpretation Accuracy Score: Indicates how well the model predicts species. Classification Report: Shows precision, recall, and F1-score for each species. Confusion Matrix: Displays where the model makes correct/incorrect classifications. Feature Importance: Helps identify which variables (bill length, flipper length, sex, island) have the most influence in predicting species.
